properties.Title: Update: Flood Watch Continued For All Points Along The Roseau River
properties.Summary:
Description: Update: This is a Manitoba Emergency Alert. Manitoba Infrastructure's Hydrologic Forecast Centre has issued a Flood Watch for all points along the Roseau River due to expected high water flows. If you are in the affected area, be watchful of local waterways as flooding is likely to occur. Do not attempt to cross fast flowing waters or waters of unknown depth. Avoid flooded areas. Follow all directions given by local authorities. Listen for updates and take all necessary precautions to stay safe. Up-to-date information is available at www.gov.mb.ca/flooding and www.manitoba511.ca or stay tuned to local media.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A major spring storm will hit the province of Quebec Sunday evening into Monday. 25 to 40 millimetres of rain is expected along the St Lawrence Valley between Montreal toward Quebec City and to the south as well as over the Ottawa Valley. However, over several regions to the north and to the east, 15 to 25 centimetres of heavy snow is expected, along with freezing rain. Heavy rain may cause flash floods and ponding on roads. Flooding is possible in low lying areas. Accumulation of heavy snow could result in broken tree limbs. A low pressure system from Texas will intensify as it tracks across New England and the Maritimes on Monday. Precipitation generated by this system will reach Southern Quebec beginning Sunday evening and intensify overnight while spreading eastward. Conditions will gradually improve late in the day on Monday. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to QCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #QCStorm.

properties.Title: Freezing Rain Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Freezing rain expected Sunday. Precipitation associated with an approaching low pressure system is expected to move into the region Sunday morning. For the higher terrain of the Dundalk Highlands, several hours of freezing rain are possible as temperatures are expected to remain near the freezing mark. Over lower elevations the freezing rain will switch to rain in the afternoon with some areas expected to receive 15 to 25 mm. The freezing rain or rain will change to snow overnight into Monday morning. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become icy and slippery. Freezing rain warnings are issued when rain falling in sub-zero temperatures creates ice build-up and icy surfaces. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A wintry mix of precipitation expected Sunday night through Tuesday. A low pressure system is expected to approach the province from the southwest on Sunday, then pass near southern New Brunswick on Monday before moving into the Gulf of St. Lawrence on Tuesday. Over northern New Brunswick, precipitation is expected to begin as a mix of snow and ice pellets on Sunday night. A transition through freezing rain to rain is then expected on Monday morning. Rain is likely to persist through the day on Monday before a changeover back to snow as the low pressure system pulls away on Monday night. Over southern New Brunswick, this system is currently expected to bring predominately rain, beginning on Sunday night. A brief changeover to snow is possible on Monday night as the low moves away. Precipitation will taper off over all areas through the day on Tuesday. Total rainfall amounts of 20 to 40 millimetres are likely across the province, with the possibility of 10 centimetres or more of snow for northernmost regions of New Brunswick. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NBStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Active weather for Newfoundland next week. Meteorologists are monitoring a developing weather system that will affect the Island for the first half of next week. Current guidance suggests a prolonged event with strong winds and a variety of precipitation types. Precipitation will arrive over southwestern Newfoundland on Monday morning and spread across the Island during the day. Most areas will receive some snow on the leading edge of the system before a transition through freezing rain to rain. Over northern Newfoundland, however, precipitation will likely remain as mainly snow. Some temporary improvement can be expected during the day on Tuesday, but colder air will follow from west to east Tuesday night into Wednesday, changing precipitation back to snow, with potential for accumulation. Strong easterly winds will develop over most areas on Monday and continue through Monday night before easing on Tuesday. Gusty northerly winds will then likely follow for Tuesday night into Wednesday. The northerlies should subside Wednesday night as the system finally pulls away. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.
Expires: 2019-04-14T08:56:50-00:00
